segments.text: Full-time center managers.
And they had their respective areas that they were out constantly seeing what we could do.
Need study.
Learn need study conference.
And then the divisions, so we wouldn't have any conflict with divisions, they signed their staff to that center.
And those staff didn't report it to their head of the division.
Didn't report to the city manager.
The center manager had no administrative control over any of the people.
All his was from facilities.
Provided need studies.
Making damn sure the door was open when they were supposed to be in social work and so on.
And that was probably the greatest thing we did during my tenure when we created those centers.
We were much more cost-effective in delivering our services.
We had availability of lots of good professional help.
You know, you might just need a lawyer for a two-hour presentation here to take into an accident investigation or whatever.
But we had those available parts in these centers because it's all located in the major area.
And that was probably what we did.
best decisions that I made there that particular time.
Not only for the engineering convention center, but for the entire university system.
Because we give them another organization representing this grand system.
And they were always first class operations.
There was no piggyback.
Always first class.
And when we started the
Rig training, all field rig training.
See, the independent drillers come to me.
They said, well, we've got, this is about 12 years, come back in the early 80s.
We need some trained rig workers.
So I said, well, here's what we're going to take.
And I said, we have to have a rig.
We have to have this.
And the independent drillers, so they can give us a rig to train on.
They give us the, they underwrote the program, which was rather expensive.
Billy Mack's kid went through it.
So that was a great success.
It got us a lot of publicity with the legislature.
Bill Clements come out and he was governor.
Oh, the city of Abilene was giving a big barbecue for our facilities and he invited them to make it.
Looking back on those 19 years, is there any area of service, I don't mean geographic area, but any topic that you wish you all could have done more?
Were you frustrated that you couldn't have served this or this or this industry?
No, we couldn't serve them.
We had no boundaries.
See, the Engineering Extension Service is the only agency in the state of Texas that has a statewide mandate to provide probation and technical training on the extension basis.
We had no conduct.
We saw something like you mentioned, but we got on it.
We jumped on it right away.
And normally in all those cases, there's some agency, some trade association or some
to take the lead role in it as far as the money raises and so on.
What were your favorite groups to work with?
There must have been some that were more pleasant than others, though.
I don't know.
I was pretty close to the telephone association.
I was pretty close to the electric co-ops.
I was close to the fire people throughout the state of Texas.
Who were the key state officials that you worked with?
Was that 19 years?
Mm-hmm.
No, but you can name your favorites, the ones that you would say thank you to.
I guess the one that probably was my favorite, and I don't know why I say it.
But anyway, I like Mark White.
Mark White and I, too, Jill Reynolds.
See, Joe Reynolds and White was in the law practice together, and then White was his junior member.
And then when he made Secretary of State, of course, I knew White when he was only with Reynolds in his law firm.
And Mark White, Secretary of State, come on up and run for governor.
I felt that he was the only governor I really, really knew, you know, for any future.
I mean, I've known all the government, but I mean, you really know them.
So I guess that's one reason I felt it close to him.
Of course, Bill Preston helped me out an awful lot.
Anytime I wanted an appointment with any senator or representative, I could call Bill if you'd have an appointment.
This was while he was state chairman.
Well, while he was a representative and as he served, you know, he served as chairman of the state of the House Appropriation Committee for about 10 or 12 years.
Whenever I was in a department with any senator or House of Representatives, I'd call him Bill.
He'd have a department.
Of course, Bill Moore, he was in the Senate.
I had done a lot of other work for Bill Moore on his outside.
He had that back at A&M.
I wrote the chart for that back at A&M.
I talked about that.
Can you give me an example of lobbying at work where you called somebody and they made the wheels turn?
Describe it.
For a specific project?
If there was one, you can think of?
Yeah, I can think of one from far.
There was a big push to create
two or three more fire fields in the state of Texas.
And they didn't want to be a part of A&M's.
They wanted to create their own, take a bunch of volunteer fire departments.
They thought, well, they should have their own fire field.
No way in the world it could ever support them.
But still, volunteer fire departments carry a lot around in rural areas with elected representatives.
And so they put on a push to create a fire field somewhere out of the Woodlands area.
Now this was long before the Woodlands was there.
And they bypassed us completely.
And I got a call one day.
A member of the representative's name was down in that area.
He said, what did I think about the, whatever, it was Missouri County that was pushing so hard.
I think Missouri County was pushing so hard to tell you what it was, Harris County.
I said, well, it's a very expensive training program.
I said, it's not cheap.
I said, you've got to have good training.
You've got to be damn careful.
And I said, true, fuel's expensive, and you've got to burn.
You can't just light a match and say, here, now we're going to go put it out.
I said, you've got to.
If you're going to have any fire training or those types of training, you've got to have hands-on training.
They've got to smell the heat and feel the heat.
But anyway, so.
He said, well, they're putting this consortium together.
I know that they're going to be coming to us for appropriation.
And so we got that stopped.
Now, the way I stopped it, I went down to the organizer.
And I said, tell me, what do y'all guys want?
What do you want?
Tell me what you want.
Give me an opportunity to say no.
So finally, what the big gripe was, there was a volunteer fire department, they didn't have anybody place to train on Saturday.
They opened the damn fire field on Saturday morning.
And that was their big gripe.
You know, they worked five days a week, and they didn't have any place to, come on, it was too expensive depending on nights and so forth.
And so I said, hey, what's the problem?
What time do you want it?
You want it to open it at 10 on Saturday?
Burn it till 6.
But we killed that one.
But another, at the same time, they were trying to get one out in West Texas.
And the word got to them then what we did.
Then they used the excuse that we live too far away.
We can't come that distance.
All right, can you give an example of where you needed some help in the legislature?
You needed to get a bill passed or some funding and give an example of where some people stepped up and helped the extension service.
No, I'll request it.
state-appropriate money.
The only state-appropriate money, the way I used my state-appropriate money was from the volunteer fire departments in the rural water district.
See, the rest of this is $3 million.
They didn't support our programs like power and great television.
No, we never, I don't ever, I didn't, I presented my, I worked with the LBP.
I had the LBB over two months before anybody else did, and I was taking it to what my request was going to be.
But I had problems that the legislature couldn't fuss about.
Volunteer fire department, rural water districts.
They couldn't fuss at themselves.
And it was, you know, even though we had a $39 million budget, it only cost the state $3 million.
And we didn't even have any in-house fights with the board or other agencies.
In fact, I had
on numerous occasions, challenged that extension service to get their money the way I got money.
And John Hutchison, one time, had Bill Moore and, I don't know, four or five others, along with, at that time, I don't know who was the chancellor of the system, I guess he was Dr. Erickson.
But anyway, he had them on, and his main complaint was that he couldn't compete with us.
He had a different clientele.
You might come back and tell me a poor group of politics.
Alright, now you reported to Benson and Calhoun under Dr. Williams when you were first.
Dr. Williams has the heart attack and then the system is recreated, the chancellor of the system recreated in 76.
And Jarvis Miller becomes president.
Ludicke went in and served for Williams.
Right.
And tell them about working with General Ludicke.
No problem.
He was a general and I was a colonel, so I had to say yes sir and I knew it, but I didn't argue with him.
How long did it take him to make up his mind about something?
Well, when they told me I was going to move the headquarters over to Henderson Hall,
At that time, Fred told me, now this is temporary.
And Dr. Wheaton told me this is temporary.
But they've all agreed with me that we had to get out of there.
It was ISO for the university.
And that's the approach I took.
It's not for me.
Now this is from that down at the south?
The business hall, yeah.
So Ludicke was in command when they were going to let the contract for Henderson Hall fix that.
And...
When I went down there to see the plants, they had my reproduction shop up on the third floor.
And I always had an old reproduction center.
You may say that was wrong.
I admit it was probably wrong.
But in industrial economics, I had my own reproduction center.
So I could control the time.
I could move my projects around any way I wanted to.
So I had to deliver them.
But I had a reproduction shop for day one.
It had a lot of people managed.
Now, this was for printing materials?
Yes.
All my artistic work.
Because all mine was sponsored research.
And, you know, when I brought down, and I had Exxon on, I had contracts for Exxon for seven or eight straight years.
And you made it to their board.
Well, they expected a first-class presentation.
They didn't want to see some carbon paper stuck out.
So, I mean, I had, that was quality.
That's, that was, and that was built into the price.
To operate that thing, that was built into the price.
But anyway.
When I went down to see him down at that time, I said, you know, we can't have that reproduction facility on the third floor.
I said, we only got one little bitty elevator.
And I said, there'll be stuff coming up and down.
And of course, I'd gone into really, you know, developing good lesson plans, good technical manuals.
And we had quite a reproduction shop still do that.
And they built that building.
And by the way, you know, we even paid for our building.
We built that $250,000 building out at the annex.
We built that $500,000 Fred Benson.
He put $500,000 out of the engineering firm.
I put $500,000 out of the engineering firm.
That long building, we built that.
Has this material.
I built that out of my fees, you know.
But to ask her whether it was right or wrong, I operated the engineering extension service as you would.
I charged for everything.
There was no...
I mean, it was all built into the price.
And so we were able to do these kind of things.
But anyway, we got that, so General Lukey said, I don't know anything about reproductions.
I said, well, let's put it down on the first floor so people can get in and get out.
And we moved that down.
Well, I called, who'd have had that before?
Who had that?
Whoever had that chopper, he couldn't really do it.
And General Lukey, out on the phone, he said, make those things.
Right from his office.
Who was that guy that had that?
Pam, I don't remember.
All right, then when General Ludeke steps aside, then Frank.
Let's see.
That's when Jarvis comes in.
Jarvis is president.
And Dr. Williams is here for another couple of years.
Right.
How did your reporting process change then?
To whom did you report?
Well, they made Pinson's vice president of engineering.
So I still reported up to him for that.
Okay.
They didn't have, I guess I reported directly to Jarvis to continue at Peyton because I know I never did go up through Prescott.
Okay.
To my knowledge, they didn't.
But now, you know, I'd give them a continuing education after five years.
You know, I only took that job for five years.
So after five years, I'll continue the education.
And that fifth year came up just about the time Jarvis took over.
Okay.
All right.
So you then, by and large, reported to the system, not through the president's office.
Well, I can't say that because I had to make my budget presentation one year with Jarvis.
Okay.
All right, when he would have a staff meeting of his key people, did you meet with them?
All right, did Dr. Williams, when he gathered the agencies, you met with them when he was chancellor?
Well, one or two meetings we had, yes.
All right, then when he left, Frank Hubert became the chancellor.
Did the routine change at all?
He was a Fred Benson man, you knew that, Frank Hubert.
The first thing he told me, the first thing he did when he became chancellor was Fred Benson's salary.
He liked Fred and Dean Hubert.
I think they were family friends too.
All right, then take me on up through the 80s.
Were there any changes in the routine with different presidents and different chancellors?
Well, of course, Richardson took over in 84.
All right, wait.
We skipped the man from Purdue.
No, Hanson.
Hanson.
He was chancellor.
Well, it was about 84 when he was.
Oh, and Richardson became dean of engineering?
Oh, I'm sorry.
Yeah, yeah.
He became dean of engineering.
All right.
And he was also vice chancellor.
Describe his management style.
Was it, it was less direct than Benson and Calhoun had been?
Herb never, the whole time that he was there, maybe before the time I left, Herb never said a crossword.
Herb and I got along superbly.
I can't say enough good things about Herb Richardson and where I come from.
He never objected to a thing I wanted to do.
He proved everything I sent down there.
I met with him once a month, and there was no problem.
Herb's problems was caused by his dad, Jack Flipsey, Ken Hall, and we only had one conflict.
Now, you've got to realize, I'm a very organized person.
I believe in an organization chart.
I believe it, and I follow it.
But anyway, you want me to put this on tape?
Cut it off.
Let me just talk a little bit.
As you look back, you served 19 years under a number of different presidents and chancellors.
I'm not going to ask the negative, but in the positive, to which ones would you give the highest?
As many as you want to.
Which ones deserve the highest credit?
During that 19-year period?
Of course, I'd have to say Dr. Liggins would take number one.
Why?
Well, I just think he's more knowledgeable about the types of programs that the engineering protection services have.
I think if he...
He accepted them on their merit, not as second class.
He never did give me the treatment that we were second class to anybody, or to anybody else.
He always was fair.
He was very easy to talk to.
Who else?
Well, of course, Mr. Benson.
I'm taking him from the top down now.
Mr. Benson and I had such a long-term relationship with each other.
We had it from about 55 to 54, whenever he became 15, until he got totally retired.
We had a good relationship after he retired.
Fred was always to the point, which I like.
Fred had a lot of characteristics that I like.
He always, if you're going to go out of town with him, you say you pick him up at 7.30, he was standing out on the court waiting for you at 7.30.
He'd always ask you if he was going to go to a meeting, whether it be a legislative meeting, like, Jim, is there anything you want me to say?
He'd always ask me that question.
Is there anything you want me to comment on?
And I always said no.
I think Frederick was a very smart individual.
He certainly commanded the
the attention of a lot of people.
When he spoke, a lot of people listened.
And I admired that.
So I'd have to put him off the top.
And of course, the next man was Calhoun.
I always talked a lot about Calhoun.
He had a lot of working relationships together.
But in my opinion, I'm not saying one was better than the other, but in my opinion, we had a completely different type of leadership.
After the middle 80s, it was completely different from 84.
Did it become more bureaucratic?
Yes, it was strictly bureaucratic.
You didn't feel at ease picking up the phone and calling them.
I never did it in the first place, but I always knew that I could if I wanted to talk to Dr. Williams or Calhoun.
I didn't have to worry about Dr. Williams or Calhoun chewing me out for calling Dr. Williams or vice versa.
Mr. Benson, you know, I didn't ever do it.
to my knowledge, but I always felt comfortable in doing such a thing like that.
We were more, in my opinion, we were more professional there.
We respected each other more.
We had a great deal of respect for each other.
And I think that was probably the one ingredient that made those change, and I think it forward to the time I retired in 92.
We had a closeness.
I talked to them as my friend, and not only as my boss, but my friend.
All right.
Now, other than your senior partners, whom did you turn to for advice and counsel and input most often?
To my committees.
I had advisory committees in every sector of my engineering station service program, made up of the leaders in their field.
Like the telephone associations, I'd have top telephone members.
I had somebody from the power companies.
And we had advisory committees.
We had one whole advisory committee for the engineering intensive, had one meeting with you.
And I'd call it in various parts of the state.
My other committee members would, you know, just pick up the phone and ask them.
And I kept them informed.
And if it was on my telephone committee, you got, and I didn't delusion with everything, but the things they ought to see, I sent it to them.
But that's who I got help from, my users.
As you look back, can you think of any decisions you wish that Texas A&M had made that it didn't make?
Well, I think they should have gone for it.
No, I can't say that because I don't have the background.
All right.
Let's talk about that a minute.
Co-education.
higher admission requirements, racial integration, broadening the curriculum, non-compulsory core, all those came in the 60s.
Did those affect your effort?
No.
No, they helped my effort.
You'd be surprised as to how many people, you know, I always traveled with an Indian detention car on the sign up with my Roman billboard.
And you'd be surprised if the number of people would stop me and ask me questions or give them information.
I never took a trip that I didn't come back that I didn't have four or five requests for information.
And the question was, it's like you had.
This girl was affected.
Everybody helped.
The only one that's hurting it is people who don't want to join the program.
Now, you rode to Austin for a number of years to reserve meetings with Earl Rudder.
With Earl, I only went over there about six months with him because I'd always assigned a driver out of my unit to drive for him.
And when I quit that, it's because the last treaty that I assigned as a driver, they got him in West Point.
Oh, I see, I see.
But I only filled in there for a period of about six months, I guess.
So, all right, during those years that you and Mr. Rutter were going to the same meeting then in Austin, describe your relationship with him.
Well, of course, Mr. Rudder was a major general, and I was a colonel.
And so, rank-wide, we were miles apart, and I respected him.
I always addressed John Rudder as General Rudder.
I never one time let myself down around John Rudder.
I always was reasonably formal.
What he did was he was going to his meeting on Monday night, and, you know, he'd have to be back.
He'd be back about 11.30, 12 o'clock.
Mr. Mudder, Mr. Rudder, nominally on the way back to 11.
And he had the ability that he could go to sleep.
He said, well, what did y'all discuss?
Well, we discussed the military quite a bit.
We discussed my unit.
I had a better group.
We discussed military personnel quite a bit.
The university, the only thing that would come up about the university, you know, he'd ask you some questions that had no answer.
He'd say, well, let's say, I don't think he ever asked this question.
He'd just say, these are the types of questions he'd ask.
Well, has making the Corps adoption of the person coming to the university, that had any effect on you?
You know, I'd say, me personally?
He'd say, well, personally and otherwise.
I'd say, no.
We're living in a different world.
And, you know, I said, I wouldn't take all the money in the world from my years I spent in the Corps, Cadets.
I said, that was in 1940.
And I said, I've got two sons.
And I said, they're both in the Corps, but I guarantee you, I didn't push them in the Corps.
They went there on their own.
But we never did get into personalities.
We never did with me, because, as I say, I was two ranks below him.
I didn't have any relationship with him as him being my boss other than in the military.
Can you share any anecdotes or amusing or interesting things that happened going to or from that involved Mr. Rutter?
No, but did anything ever go wrong?
Did you all ever have a flat or get there late or anything like that?
Well, I got stopped several times for speed.
Oh, really?
Oh, yeah.
And what would the Highway Patrol say?
Oh, he gave you... It didn't matter whose car that was?
We were driving a military vehicle.
Mr. Rudd would like to get where he's going fast.
I don't know if anybody's ever told you that before.
No, I didn't know that.
He wasn't allergic to pushing the metal to the pedal.
And I don't know how many tickets he got, but with me, I got for him.
All right, who paid the tickets?
I got the tickets.
Okay, so you don't know.
You don't know?
Okay.
I never did ask.
He always would take the ticket from me.
All right.
He took the one ticket from me.
All right.
When the Highway Patrol would stop, did it impress the Highway Patrol that here was a Major General?
Well, that only happened one time with me.
And I doubt if that Highway Patrol knew a Major General from me.
All right.
So he didn't even talk to the person in the back seat.
Okay.
I'm just talking about one time.
It was late at night.
Mr. Rudder, have a sense of humor?
Very good sense of humor.
Can you give me any example of his?
I told you, I had an infantry battle boot, and we always had the army command to come down while we were going to get camp.
So Mr. Rudder always used my battle boot as one to demonstrate and put on their submission.
So one day we was having this general come down and float army command, and I said, now Kim, I want to do this.
We'll be out here, train you at 11 o'clock, get me a map, tell me specifically where you're going to be with all of these.
So I said, fine, I've done this a dozen times for me.
So we decided to have an infantry tank, an attack.
And I picked out a beautiful valley, and it had a nice roll of trees.
And we'd come right, so I said, no, we're going to come right down with our tanks.
And so, Mr. Rudder and the other general drove up.
I went out and reported to him.
Oh, he said, oh.
And I said to this gentleman, I said, now there's a lot of wood rattlers here.
And I said, in fact, I said, there's one right by your foot.
Oh, he's a little bit short there.
And I said, with your boots on, it won't bother you.
But anyway, we went up to this thing.
By that time, boy, everything was different.
I mean, I had that deal.
I always had the time right there.
They'd unload all the time, and they'd get in for a time.
So Mr. Rubber asked him to walk it off.
But anyway, I told this gentleman, I said, sir, I said, there's another rattlesnake that crashed by your foot.
And I just put my foot back there and stopped that.
He said, didn't bite me, did it?
I said, no, sir, he didn't bite you.
So I got into his car.
He said, now, are you sure that rattlesnake didn't bite me?
I said, officer, he didn't bite you.
Mr. Rubber said, I'd like to see you at 1 o'clock today.
And I thought he was going to get me for telling me about the damn rattlesnake.
He said, god damn it, Colonel.
He said, when I said, made it realistic, he said, I didn't want you to run over us.
I said, well, I said, at that slope, I said, you know, I said, to make it realistic, we had to come take part of that slope.
He said, I didn't want it that damn close.
As far as you know, when Earl Rutter was president of A&M, to whom did he turn for advice most often?
Whose advice did he listen to most carefully?
You mean from in-house?
All right, then you.
It might surprise you, though, if you didn't know.
It might be some instructor down there or something.
You said in-house, all right, let's go out of the house.
Away from the campus, whose advice did he hear?
Well, he had here to the board's advice.
He had a lot of respect for the board.
Who were the key board members during his day?
Well, let's see.
When did he die, in 59?
Oh, in 70.
In 69?
Okay.
He died in March of 70.
Sterling Evans, Zachary, Clyde Wells.
Clyde Wells was on it, and Mrs. Wilson from Lubbock was on it.
And I don't know whether Norman Mosier was on it at that time.
I don't either.
And I don't know whether Mr.
